## What may need to change in `UserEntity`

Only add fields when your database genuinely needs them.

For example, you may add:

```java
@Column(name = "ping_resource_id")
private String pingResourceId;
```

because Ping returns its own SCIM resource ID, which is needed later for:

```text
PATCH /partners-BE-AP74737/{id}
DELETE /partners-BE-AP74737/{id}
```

Optionally:

```java
@Enumerated(EnumType.STRING)
@Column(name = "ping_sync_status")
private PingSyncStatus pingSyncStatus;

@Column(name = "ping_last_synced_at")
private Instant pingLastSyncedAt;

@Column(name = "ping_last_error")
private String pingLastError;
```

But do **not** rename fields like:

```java
firstName -> givenName
lastName -> sn
email -> mail
phoneNumber -> mobile
```

Those are Ping/LDAP attribute names and should stay confined to your Ping mapper.

One possible issue in your entity is:

```java
@Column(name = "status", nullable = false)
private String status;
```

That is valid, but using an enum is safer:

```java
@Enumerated(EnumType.STRING)
@Column(name = "status", nullable = false)
private UserStatus status;
```

Then map it:

```java
request.setStatus(user.getStatus().name());
```

So the answer is: keep the entity as-is for those six attributes; update the mapper, and only add `pingResourceId` and sync metadata if you need to manage Ping updates and failures.



